03994nam a22007575i 9780823257461DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232574617 a10.1515/97808232574612doi  a(DE-B1597)555071  a(OCoLC)1175625039  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB380 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a1841 aRapp, Jennifer R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOrdinary Oblivion and the Self Unmoored :bReading Plato's Phaedrus and Writing the Soul /cJennifer R. Rapp. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. Replete and Porous -- t1. The Teeming Body -- t2. The Fluid Body -- t3. The Torn Body -- tConclusion. Ghost Ribs of Discourse beyond the Phaedrus -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRapp begins with a question posed by the poet Theodore Roethke: "Should we say that the self, once perceived, becomes a soul?" Through her examination of Plato's Phaedrus and her insights about the place of forgetting in a life, Rapp answers Roethke's query with a resounding Yes. In so doing, Rapp reimagines the Phaedrus, interprets anew Plato's relevance to contemporary life, and offers an innovative account of forgetting as a fertile fragility constitutive of humanity.Drawing upon poetry and comparisons with other ancient Greek and Daoist texts, Rapp brings to light overlooked features of the Phaedrus, disrupts longstanding interpretations of Plato as the facile champion of memory, and offers new lines of sight onto (and from) his corpus. Her attention to the Phaedrus and her meditative apprehension of the permeable character of human life leave our understanding of both Plato and forgetting inescapably altered. Unsettle everything you think you know about Plato, suspend the twentieth-century entreaty to "Never forget," and behold here a new mode of critical reflection in which textual study and humanistic inquiry commingle to expansive effect.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 4aOblivion. 4aPhaedrus. 4aPlato. 4aSoul. 4adialogical. 4aforgetting. 4afragility. 4areading. 4aremembrance. 4aselfhood. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071187540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823257461zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823257461423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823257461.jpg  a978-3-11-071187-5  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK